You have spaces before status. Use xargs instead tr -d &#39;\r&#39;.

    GOOD=&quot;status: System is already up to date&quot;
    
    STATUS=$(grep status file.txt | tail -1 | xargs)
            
    if [ &quot;$STATUS&quot; != &quot;$GOOD&quot; ]
    then
        echo &quot;There is a new version available&quot;
    else
        echo &quot;You are up to date&quot;
    fi

How about using the `pattern matching` with the `[[ .. ]]` command instead of
`[` or `test` command.
Here is a tiny example of the usage:

    target=&quot;aaa&quot;
    string=&quot;   aaa___&quot;

    if [[ $string == *$target* ]]; then
        echo &quot;match&quot;
    fi

You don&#39;t have to care about the leading/trailing extra characters with
the pattern matching.  
Then you can say something like:

    good=&quot;status: System is already up to date&quot;
    status=$(grep &quot;status&quot; &quot;file.txt&quot; | tail -1)

    if [[ $status == *$good* ]]; then
         echo &quot;You are up to date&quot;
    else
         echo &quot;There is a new version available&quot;
    fi

Note that you don&#39;t have to double-quote the variables within the [[ and ]].  
Hope this helps.

